<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Decade of Catastrophe, Natural and Man-Made</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Earth shook, erupted, collapsed, caught fire and spawned
vicious storms with regularity through the 1980s, killing tens of
thousands of people around the world. But the decade's cataclysms
also included new forms of man-made tragedy.
   Here is a review of some of the decade's worst disasters:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NATURAL DISASTERS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   MAY 18, 1980 _ Mount St. Helens volcano in Washington state
erupts with power equivalent to 500 Hiroshima bombs. This blast and
two that followed within the next month killed 57 people and caused
over $3 billion in damage.
   OCT. 11, 1980 _ Earthquake in Algeria kills 6,000 and leaves
400,000 homeless.
   NOV. 23, 1980 _ More than 3,000 killed and 300,000 left homeless
when earthquake, Europe's deadliest in 65 years, devastates
southern Italy.
   MAY 24-25, 1985 _ Cyclone out of Bay of Bengal comes ashore in
Bangladesh; some 11,000 killed.
   SEPT. 19, 1985 _ Earthquake strikes Mexico City; 7,000 die.
   NOV. 13-14, 1985 _ Colombia's erupting Nevado del Ruiz volcano
melts snowcaps, causing a massive mudflow that buries town of
Armero, killing 25,000 people.
   AUG. 21, 1986 _ Cloud of toxic gas from volcanic Lake Nios in
Cameroon envelops several villages, killing 1,746 people and
injuring 874.
   MAY 7, 1987 _ Approximate start of series of Chinese forest
fires that kill 191 people.
   SEPT. 12-16, 1988 _ Hurricane Gilbert, Category 5 storm with
winds up to 160 mph, strikes Jamaica, Cayman Islands, Mexico and
Texas, killing some 300 people.
   OCT. 19-25, 1988 _ Hurricane Joan-Miriam kills 184 in Central
America.
   DEC. 7, 1988 _ Earthquake registering 6.9 on Richter scale kills
25,000 in Soviet Armenia.
   SEPT. 17-21, 1989 _ Hurricane Hugo sweeps through Caribbean and
into Charleston, S.C., with 135 mph winds, killing 62.
   OCT. 17, 1989 _ Earthquake measuring 7.1 on Richter scale
rattles San Francisco Bay area, killing 67 and causing estimated $7
billion in property damage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TRANSPORTATION DISASTERS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   AUG. 12, 1985 _ In decade's worst air disaster, Japan Air Lines
747 crashes into a mountain near Tokyo, killing 520. Four
passengers survive crash.
   DEC. 12, 1985 _ Arrow Air charter DC-8 crashes shortly after
takeoff from Gander, Newfoundland; all 256 people aboard die,
including 248 U.S. servicemen.
   AUG. 16, 1987 _ In decade's worst U.S. domestic plane crash,
Northwest Airlines MD-80 crashes on takeoff at Detroit Metropolitan
Airport, killing 156. One passenger, a 4-year-old girl, survives.
   DEC. 20, 1987 _ Philippine passenger ferry Dona Paz collides
with tanker and sinks; more than 3,000 holiday travelers killed.
   JUNE 4, 1989 _ Gas explosion in Ural mountains of Soviet Union
engulfs two passing trains, killing 645.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>INDUSTRIAL ACCIDENTS and FIRES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   MARCH 27, 1980 _ Offshore platform housing oil workers capsizes
in North Sea off Norway, killing 123 men.
   NOV. 21, 1980 _ Fire at MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas kills 87
people.
   FEB. 15, 1982 _ World's largest floating oil drilling rig, Ocean
Ranger, sinks in storm off coast of Newfoundland, killing 84.
   DEC. 3, 1984 _ Leak of deadly methyl isocyanate gas at Union
Carbide plant in Bhopal, India, kills 3,598 people, injures 20,000.
   APRIL 26, 1986 _ Explosion and radiation leak from Soviet
Union's Chernobyl nuclear power station kills at least 31, hurts
some 300. Later unconfirmed report says 250 died.
   SEPT. 16, 1986 _ South African gold mine fire kills 177.
   DEC. 31, 1986 _ Fire at Dupont Plaza hotel in San Juan, Puerto
Rico, kills 97. Three hotel employees later plead guilty to arson
charges.
   JULY 6, 1988 _ Piper Alpha oil platform explodes in North Sea,
killing 167.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
